## Migration: `TimedExecutor` → .NET 8

### Pattern Classification

Your code has two patterns from the skill guide:

| Pattern | Location | Replacement |
|---------|----------|-------------|
| **Timeout enforcement** | `thread.Abort()` after `Join(timeout)` fails | `CancellationTokenSource.CancelAfter` |
| **ThreadAbortException as control flow** | `catch (ThreadAbortException) { Thread.ResetAbort(); }` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |

### Why This Breaks on .NET 8

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — the runtime no longer supports forcibly injecting exceptions into threads. `Thread.ResetAbort()` is also gone (`SYSLIB0006`).

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var token = cts.Token;

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(), token);

        try
        {
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException on timeout
            return task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }
}
```

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | What to watch for |
|---------|-------------------|
| **Work doesn't actually stop** | `Task.Run` + cancellation token only prevents *starting* a new task if already cancelled. The `Func<T> work` delegate **keeps running** in the background unless it cooperates. This is the fundamental paradigm shift. |
| **CancellationTokenSource leak** | Always wrap in `using`. Leaking it causes timer leaks. |
| **Swallowing OperationCanceledException** | Only catch it at this top-level orchestration point to convert to `TimeoutException`. |

### Making Work Actually Cancellable

The original `Thread.Abort` forcibly killed the thread. Cooperative cancellation **requires the work to opt in**. Update the signature to accept a token and check it:

```csharp
// Updated signature — pass CancellationToken through the chain
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    var token = cts.Token;

    var task = Task.Run(() => work(token), token);

    try
    {
        return task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}

// Caller example — work checks the token at regular intervals
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in largeCollection)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return ComputeResult();
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### If Work Cannot Be Modified (Uncooperative Code)

If `work` calls third-party code you can't change, cooperative cancellation won't help — the work continues running silently. In that case, move the work to a **child process** and call `Process.Kill()` on timeout. This is the only safe way to forcibly terminate uncooperative code in modern .NET.
